In Java, **method overriding** allows a subclass to provide its own version of a method already defined in its parent class. This enables **runtime polymorphism**, where the method that gets executed is determined based on the actual object type during program execution. The method signature must be exactly the same

**Syntax:**

```java
class Parent {
    void methodName() {
        // Parent version
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    @Override
    void methodName() {
        // Child version
    }
}
```

---

**Example:**

```java
// Parent class
class Animal {
    // Method to make a sound (can be overridden by subclasses)
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal makes a sound");
    }
}

// Child class that inherits from Animal
class Dog extends Animal {
    // Overriding the sound() method to provide specific behavior for Dog
    @Override
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}

// Main class to run the program
class Seedit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Create a Dog object, but refer to it using an Animal reference
        Animal a = new Dog();

        // Call the sound method — this demonstrates runtime polymorphism
        // The Dog's version of sound() is called, not Animal's
        a.sound();
    }
}
```

 **Expected Output:**

```default
Dog barks
```

